{"title_page": "It Don't Bother Me", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = It Don't Bother Me\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Bert Jansch]]\n| cover      = itdontbotherme1965.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = December 1965\n| recorded   = c. April 1965 at Pye Studios, [[Denmark Street|Denmark Street, London]]\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk music|Folk]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Transatlantic Records|Transatlantic]]\n| producer   = [[Nathan Joseph]], [[Bill Leader]] (uncredited)\n| prev_title = [[Bert Jansch (album)|Bert Jansch]]\n| prev_year  = 1965\n| next_title = [[Lucky Thirteen (Bert Jansch album)|Lucky Thirteen]]\n| next_year  = 1966\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = ''[[Allmusic]]''\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r107159|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin|title=Encyclopedia of Popular Music|year=2007|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|edition=4th|isbn=978-0195313734|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n\n'''''It Don't Bother Me''''' is the second album by [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[Folk music|folk]] musician [[Bert Jansch]], released in December 1965. The album was produced by [[Nathan Joseph]] and [[Bill Leader]], although Leader was left uncredited.<ref name=\"discography\">{{cite web|title=Bert Jansch website |url=http://www.bertjansch.com/disco.html#itdontbother |accessdate=2008-11-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205024612/http://www.bertjansch.com/disco.html |archivedate=2008-12-05 }}</ref>\n\nThe album features nine songs composed by Jansch, one by [[Alex Campbell (singer)|Alex Campbell]] (\"So Long (Been on the Road So Long)\"), and the traditional \"900 Miles\". For this last Jansch accompanies himself on the banjo rather than the steel-string acoustic guitar which he uses elsewhere. \"A Man I'd Rather Be\" features lead vocals by [[Roy Harper (singer)|Roy Harper]].<ref>[http://musicnaut.iki.fi/musicnaut/royharper/discography/guest.html A list of Roy Harper's guest appearances]</ref> \"My Lover\" also has Harper playing some additional guitar, while [[John Renbourn]] is playing the lead acoustic guitar part. \"Lucky Thirteen\" is a guitar duet with Renbourn, based on a song written by the latter and apparently recorded during the ''[[Bert and John]]'' session.<ref>See John Renbourn\u2019s [http://www.john-renbourn.com/shop/jr3.html notes on ''Bert and John''].</ref> Finally, \"Tinkers Blues\" and \"The Wheel\" are guitar instrumentals composed and performed by Jansch.\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks composed by Bert Jansch, except where indicated\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side one\n| writing credits = yes\n| title1 = Oh, My Babe\n| length1 = 3:56\n| title2 = Ring-A-Ding Bird\n| length2 = 4:39\n| title3 = Tinker's Blues\n| note3 = Instrumental\n| length3 = 1:04\n| title4 = Anti Apartheid\n| length4 = 4:02\n| title5 = The Wheel\n| note5 = Instrumental\n| length5 = 1:45\n| title6 = A Man I'd Rather Be\n| length6 = 2:04\n| title7 = My Lover\n| length7 = 4:00\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| writing credits = yes\n| title8 = It Don't Bother Me\n| length8 = 4:25\n| title9 = Harvest Your Thoughts of Love\n| length9 = 2:12\n| title10 = Lucky Thirteen\n| note10 = Instrumental\n| writer10 = [[John Renbourn]]\n| length10 = 3:30\n| title11 = As the Day Grows Longer Now\n| length11 = 3:40\n| title12 = So Long (Been On the Road So Long)\n| writer12 = [[Alex Campbell (singer)|Alex Campbell]]\n| length12 = 3:10\n| title13 = Want My Daddy Now\n| length13 = 1:33\n| title14 = 900 Miles\n| writer14 = Traditional\n| length14 = 3:03\n}}\n\n==References==\n* Sleeve notes to Bert Jansch, ''it don\u2019t bother me'' (TRA 132).\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bert Jansch}}\n\n[[Category:Bert Jansch albums]]\n[[Category:1965 albums]]\n[[Category:Transatlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Nathan Joseph]]\n[[Category:albums produced by Bill Leader]]\n\n{{1960s-folk-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = It Don't Bother Me\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Bert Jansch]]\n| cover      = itdontbotherme1965.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = December 1965\n| recorded   = c. April 1965 at Pye Studios, [[Denmark Street|Denmark Street, London]]\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk music|Folk]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Transatlantic Records|Transatlantic]]\n| producer   = [[Nathan Joseph]], [[Bill Leader]] (uncredited)\n| prev_title = [[Bert Jansch (album)|Bert Jansch]]\n| prev_year  = 1965\n| next_title = [[Lucky Thirteen (Bert Jansch album)|Lucky Thirteen]]\n| next_year  = 1966\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = ''[[Allmusic]]''\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r107159|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n\n'''''It Don't Bother Me''''' is the second album by [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[Folk music|folk]] musician [[Bert Jansch]], released in December 1965. The album was produced by [[Nathan Joseph]] and [[Bill Leader]], although Leader was left uncredited.<ref name=\"discography\">{{cite web|title=Bert Jansch website |url=http://www.bertjansch.com/disco.html#itdontbother |accessdate=2008-11-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205024612/http://www.bertjansch.com/disco.html |archivedate=2008-12-05 }}</ref>\n\nThe album features nine songs composed by Jansch, one by [[Alex Campbell (singer)|Alex Campbell]] (\"So Long (Been on the Road So Long)\"), and the traditional \"900 Miles\". For this last Jansch accompanies himself on the banjo rather than the steel-string acoustic guitar which he uses elsewhere. \"A Man I'd Rather Be\" features lead vocals by [[Roy Harper (singer)|Roy Harper]].<ref>[http://musicnaut.iki.fi/musicnaut/royharper/discography/guest.html A list of Roy Harper's guest appearances]</ref> \"My Lover\" also has Harper playing some additional guitar, while [[John Renbourn]] is playing the lead acoustic guitar part. \"Lucky Thirteen\" is a guitar duet with Renbourn, based on a song written by the latter and apparently recorded during the ''[[Bert and John]]'' session.<ref>See John Renbourn\u2019s [http://www.john-renbourn.com/shop/jr3.html notes on ''Bert and John''].</ref> Finally, \"Tinkers Blues\" and \"The Wheel\" are guitar instrumentals composed and performed by Jansch.\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks composed by Bert Jansch, except where indicated\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side one\n| writing credits = yes\n| title1 = Oh, My Babe\n| length1 = 3:56\n| title2 = Ring-A-Ding Bird\n| length2 = 4:39\n| title3 = Tinker's Blues\n| note3 = Instrumental\n| length3 = 1:04\n| title4 = Anti Apartheid\n| length4 = 4:02\n| title5 = The Wheel\n| note5 = Instrumental\n| length5 = 1:45\n| title6 = A Man I'd Rather Be\n| length6 = 2:04\n| title7 = My Lover\n| length7 = 4:00\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| writing credits = yes\n| title8 = It Don't Bother Me\n| length8 = 4:25\n| title9 = Harvest Your Thoughts of Love\n| length9 = 2:12\n| title10 = Lucky Thirteen\n| note10 = Instrumental\n| writer10 = [[John Renbourn]]\n| length10 = 3:30\n| title11 = As the Day Grows Longer Now\n| length11 = 3:40\n| title12 = So Long (Been On the Road So Long)\n| writer12 = [[Alex Campbell (singer)|Alex Campbell]]\n| length12 = 3:10\n| title13 = Want My Daddy Now\n| length13 = 1:33\n| title14 = 900 Miles\n| writer14 = Traditional\n| length14 = 3:03\n}}\n\n==References==\n* Sleeve notes to Bert Jansch, ''it don\u2019t bother me'' (TRA 132).\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bert Jansch}}\n\n[[Category:Bert Jansch albums]]\n[[Category:1965 albums]]\n[[Category:Transatlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Nathan Joseph]]\n[[Category:albums produced by Bill Leader]]\n\n{{1960s-folk-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Muso805", "label": "safe", "comment": "4 star rating from 10 volume 4th Edition Oxford University Press, EPM 2007", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/It_Don%27t_Bother_Me"}
{"title_page": "Luke Bilyk", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name= Luke Bilyk\n|image=\n|caption= Luke Bilyk, [[Teen Choice Awards]], 2013\n|birth_name= \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1994|11|10}}\n| birth_place = [[North York]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n|occupation= Actor\n|years_active= 2005\u2013present\n|home_town= \n}}\n'''Luke Bilyk''' (born November 10, 1994) is a Canadian actor. He is best known for his role as Drew Torres in ''[[Degrassi: The Next Generation]]'', which he starred on from 2010 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.postcity.com/Eat-Shop-Do/Do/July-2015/Luke-Bilyk-looks-back-on-life-as-a-Degrassi-star/|title=Luke Bilyk looks back on life as a Degrassi star|website=www.postcity.com|access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> He's also appeared in film roles such as TJ in ''[[F the Prom]]'' (2017).\n\n== Early life ==\nBilyk grew up in [[Vaughan|Vaughan, Ontario]] with three older sisters. He is of Italian, Ukrainian, German, and Jewish descent.<ref>https://www.lukebilyk.ca/about-me/biography</ref> Bilyk attended [[St. Elizabeth Catholic High School]] in Thornhill, where he was part of the Regional Arts Program for Drama.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n== Career ==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2016}}Bilyk had a recurring role as Mark in season 5 of ''[[Lost Girl]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Gooby]]''\n| Cute Kid\n| Film Debut, Movie Debut\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Hellions (film)|Hellions]]''\n| Jace\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 2017\n| ''[[Kiss and Cry (film)|Kiss and Cry]]''\n| John Servinis\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Adam's Testament]]''\n| Adam Gable\n|\n|-\n| ''[[F the Prom]]''\n| TJ\n| \n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Black Conflux]]''\n| Donovan\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable