inners \u2013 The Accountant|website=www.theaccountant-online.com|access-date=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nPwC Singapore won the Best Practice Award in 2016 from the Institute of Singapore Chartered Accountants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.isca.org.sg/the-institute/newsroom/media-releases/2016/august/innovation-growth-and-excellence-lauded-at-singapore-accountancy-awards/|title=Innovation, Growth and Excellence Lauded at Singapore Accountancy Awards {{!}} ISCA|website=www.isca.org.sg|language=en-US|access-date=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Australian Financial Review Client Choice Awards recognized PwC with the Market Leader Australia award for 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pwc.com.au/awards.html|title=Awards 2017|last=PricewaterhouseCoopers|work=PwC|access-date=16 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nPwC Australia has been recognized by clients as Market Leader at the Financial Review Client Choice Awards 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://clientchoiceawards.net/awards-for-firms/|title=Awards for Firms \u2013 Client Choice Awards|work=Client Choice Awards|access-date=16 May 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Brand Finance named PwC as the strongest business to business brand, and one of the world's 10 most powerful brands in their annual index.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.biznisafrica.co.za/pwc-named-strongest-business-to-business-brand/|title=PwC named strongest business to business brand \u2013 BizNis Africa|date=3 March 2016|work=BizNis Africa|access-date=30 May 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nPwC ranked #3 in DiversityInc's Top 12 Companies for Global Diversity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.diversityinc.com/diversityinc-top-12-companies-global-diversity/|title=The DiversityInc Top Companies for Global Diversity|last=Staff|first=DiversityInc|work=DiversityInc|access-date=8 June 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129042605/http://www.diversityinc.com/diversityinc-top-12-companies-global-diversity/|archive-date=29 January 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFor the second consecutive year PwC was named Global Corporate Ventures Consultancy Firm of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalcorporateventuring.com/article.php/14048/gcv-award-consultancy-of-the-year-pricewaterhousecoopers-pwc|title=GCV Award: Consultancy of the Year \u2013 PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) \u00b7 Articles \u00b7 Global Corporate Venturing|website=www.globalcorporateventuring.com|access-date=11 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nStrategy&\u2019s strategy+business publication ranked #4 in top research and think tanks globally by Global Think Tanks and Civil Societies Program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://repository.upenn.edu/think_tanks/|title=TTCSP Global Go To Think Tank Index Reports {{!}} Think Tanks and Civil Societies Program (TTCSP) {{!}} University of Pennsylvania|website=repository.upenn.edu|language=en|access-date=8 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nPwC was ranked number one on The Times Top 100 Graduate Employers for 2016, for a record-breaking 13th consecutive year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milkround.com/staticpages/12680/the-times-top-100-graduate-employers/|title=The Times Top 100 Graduate Employers {{!}} Milkround|website=www.milkround.com|language=en-GB|access-date=11 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pwc.com/jg/en/careers/students/times-top-100.html|title=The Times Top 100 Graduate Employer|last=PricewaterhouseCoopers|work=PwC|access-date=11 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor the 14th consecutive year, PwC Brazil was ranked #1 in the Audit segment on the Carta Capital magazine\u2019s list of \u2018As Empresas mais Admiradas no Brasil\u2019 (Brazil's Most Admired Companies.)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.administradores.com.br/noticias/negocios/confira-a-lista-das-empresas-mais-admiradas-do-brasil-segundo-ranking-da-carta-capital/62666/|title=Confira a lista das empresas mais admiradas do Brasil, segundo ranking da Carta Capital|last=Administradores.com|date=2 October 2012|work=Administradores.com|access-date=8 June 2017|language=pt}}</ref>\n\nPwC US was named one of Fortune's \u2018100 Best Companies to Work For\u2019 for the 11th consecutive year of 13 years on the list.<ref name=\"Fortune 100 Best: PwC\">{{cite magazine|title=Fortune 100 Best|url=http://beta.fortune.com/best-companies/pricewaterhousecoopers-23|magazine=Fortune|accessdate=1 June 2017|date=2017}}</ref>\n\nPwC India won the 2016 AMCF (Association of Management Consulting Firms) Global Spotlight Award in the Growth Strategies category.<ref name=\"IIFL: PwC India wins Association of Management Consulting Firms Spotlight Awards 2016\">{{cite web|title=PwC India wins Association of Management Consulting Firms Spotlight Awards 2016|url=http://www.indiainfoline.com/article/general-others-factiva/pwc-india-wins-association-of-management-consulting-firms-spotlight-awards-2016-116062900111_1.html|publisher=India Info Online|accessdate=1 June 2017|date=29 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Gender employment discrimination===\n{{main|Price Waterhouse v. Hopkins}}\nIn 1989, the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] held that Price Waterhouse must prove by a preponderance of the evidence that the decision regarding employment would have been the same if [[sex discrimination]] had not occurred. The accounting firm failed to prove that the same decision to postpone [[Ann Hopkins]]'s promotion to partnership would have still been made in the absence of sex discrimination, and therefore, the employment decision constituted sex discrimination under [[Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964]]. The significance of the Supreme Court's ruling was twofold. First, it established that gender stereotyping is actionable as sex discrimination. Second, it established the [[Mixed motive discrimination|mixed-motive framework]] as an evidentiary framework for proving discrimination under a disparate treatment theory even when lawful reasons for the adverse employment action are also present.<ref>Goldstein, Leslie. \"Gender Stereotyping and the Workplace: Price Waterhouse v. Hopkins (1989).\" 2006. The Constitutional and Legal Rights of Women, 3rd ed. Los Angeles: Roxbury, 2006. 167\u201375. Print.''</ref> Hopkins's candidacy for partnership was put on indefinite hold. She eventually resigned and sued the company for [[occupational sexism]], arguing that her lack of promotion came after pressure to walk, talk, dress, and act more \"femininely.\"<ref name=\"Levit\">{{cite book|last1=Levit|first1=Nancy|title=The Gender Line: Men, Women, and the Law|date=1998|publisher=New York University Press|page=212|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GUldDkj_mg4C&pg=PA212#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=27 December 2014|isbn=9780814751220}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990 a Federal district judge in Washington ordered the firm to make Hopkins a partner. It was the first time in which a court awarded partnership in a professional company as a remedy for sexual or race-based discrimination.<ref name=\"NYTimes: Partnership in Firm Awarded to Victim of Sex Bias\">{{cite news|last1=Lewin|first1=Tamar|title=Partnership in Firm Awarded to Victim of Sex Bias|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/16/us/partnership-in-firm-awarded-to-victim-of-sex-bias.html|publisher=NYTimes|accessdate=11 May 2017|date=16 May 1990}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the suit, the firm received media attention due to its discriminatory labor practices towards males as well. Although incidents of such labor marginalization take place rarely, there were several cases of unfair work treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/relationships/fatherhood/11206484/Father-wins-sex-discrimination-case-after-request-to-work-part-time-rejected.html|title=Father wins sex discrimination case after request to work part-time rejected|website=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Tax issues===\n* PwC received $55m from [[Caterpillar Inc.]] to develop a [[tax avoidance]] scheme, according to an investigation of the US Senate. Profits valued at $8bn were shifted from the US to Switzerland, which allegedly made it possible to save more than $2.4bn in US taxes over a decade. In Switzerland profits were taxed at 4%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/mar/31/caterpillar-avoid-4billion-us-taxes-senate-report |title=Senate report claims Caterpillar avoided $2.4bn in US taxes|newspaper=The Guardian|date=31 March 2014|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref> A PricewaterhouseCoopers partner who was involved in designing the tax savings plan commented: \u201cWe'll all be retired when this .\u200a.\u200a. comes up on audit.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/big-four-audit-firms-behind-global-profit-shifting-20141106-11i08q.html |title=Big four audit firms behind global profit shifting|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=6 November 2014|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref>\n* In 1990, the US [[Internal Revenue Service]] seized most of the assets of [[Willie Nelson]], claiming he owed $32 million in back taxes, including penalties and interest. He sued Price Waterhouse, contending that they put him into [[tax shelter]]s that were later disallowed by the IRS.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CEFD7113FF931A3575AC0A967958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |quote=$32 million bill for delinquent taxes ... pay for the $45 million lawsuit Mr. Nelson filed last year against his former accountants at Price Waterhouse, who he contends put him into ill-advised tax shelters. The Government ruled against many of the tax shelters, and the I.R.S. later disallowed many of the tax benefits that Mr. Nelson claimed. |work=New York Times | title=Willie Nelson Hopes for a Hit; So Does the I.R.S | date=2 September 1991}}</ref> The lawsuit was settled for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D04E6DF1739F937A35752C1A963958260 | work=The New York Times | title=Tax Shelter of Rich and Famous Has Final Date in Court | date=4 November 1995}}</ref>\n\n===American International Group Inc.===\n''Business Week'' said that PwC was [[American International Group]] Inc.'s auditor through years of \"questionable dealings.\" AIG on 30 March 2005 said that deals with a [[Barbados]]-based insurance company, for instance, may have been incorrectly accounted for over the past 14 years, because an AIG-affiliated company may have been secretly covering that insurer's losses.<ref name=\"businessweek\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20050407205849/http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/05_15/b3928047_mz011.htm Tough Questions For AIG's Auditors \u2013 Regulators are probing if PwC let the financial shenanigans slip through] Businessweek, Joseph Weber, Mike McNamee, Marcia Vickers and Diane Brady, 11 April 2005</ref>\n\n''BusinessWeek'' said that PwC appeared to have \"dropped the ball\" on the deals between AIG and [[Berkshire Hathaway]] Inc.'s General Re Corp. General Re transferred $500 million in anticipated claims and premiums to AIG. ''BusinessWeek'' asked: \"Did the auditor do its job by verifying that AIG was assuming risk on claims beyond the $500 million, thus allowing AIG to account for the deal as insurance? That's Accounting 101 in any reinsurance transaction.\"<ref name=\"businessweek\"/>\n\nPwC was also criticised by several witnesses during the investigation into AIG's collapse, after the insurer was unable to fulfil its collateral obligations to [[Goldman Sachs]]. The insurer was expected to cover the difference in value between the [[credit default swap]] contracts it had sold to Goldman Sachs, however the head of the unit at AIG disagreed with the valuation that Goldman presented. According to a memo published by ''Business Insider'', witnesses wondered how PwC was signing off on the accounts for both AIG and Goldman Sachs, when they were using different valuation methods for the swaps contracts (and therefore booked different values for them in their accounts).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/joe-cassano-on-goldman-aig-dispute-2016-3?r=US&IR=T|title=We just got a new insight into a crucial crisis-era dispute between Goldman Sachs and AIG|website=Business Insider|date=11 March 2016|accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===ChuoAoyama Suspension===\n{{Nihongo|ChuoAoyama Audit Corporation|\u4e2d\u592e\u9752\u5c71\u76e3\u67fb\u6cd5\u4eba|Ch\u016b\u014d-Aoyama Kansa H\u014djin}} was the Japanese affiliate of assurance service of PwC from April 2000 to 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbs.edu/faculty/Publication%20Files/10-088.pdf|title=Audit Quality and Auditor Reputation: Evidence from Japan}}</ref> In May 2006, the Financial Services Agency of Japan suspended ChuoAoyama from provision of some statutory auditing services for two months<ref>{{cite document|title=In May 2006, the Japanese Financial Services Agency (FSA) suspended ChuoAoyama for two months|ssrn=1557231}}</ref> following the collapse of cosmetics company Kanebo, of which three of the partners were found assisting with accounting fraud for boosting earnings by the company of about $1.9 billion over the course of five years. The accountants got suspended prison terms up to 18 months from the Tokyo District Court after the judge deemed them to have played a \"passive role\" in the crime.<ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20060810a2.html CPAs in Kanebo fraud avoid prison], ''The Japan Times'' (registration required), 10 August 2006.</ref> The suspension was the first ever imposed on a major accounting firm in the country. Many of the firm's largest clients were forced to find replacement auditors before the suspension began that July.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1194088,00.html#ixzz1IokjSHHm |title=Japan's Regulators Get Tough |date=15 May 2006 |author=Jim Frederick |work=Time}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the suspension of ChuoAoyama, PwC acted quickly to stem any possible client attrition as a result of the scandal. It set up the PricewaterhouseCoopers Aarata, and some of ChuoAoyama's accountants (but most of the international divisions) moved to the new firm. ChuoAoyama resumed operations on 1 September 2006 under the Misuzu name. However, by this point the two firms combined had 30% fewer clients than did ChuoAoyama prior to its suspension. Misuzu was dissolved in July 2007.<ref>[http://www.fraud-magazine.com/article.aspx?id=415 New Japanese Internal Controls Framework] Fraud Magazine, November/December 2007</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2007/08/02/business/misuzu-audit-disbands-after-39-years-scandals/#.WRLDrsbYWUk|title=Misuzu Audit disbands after 39 years, scandals|last=Kyodo News|date=2 August 2007|website=The Japan Times|access-date=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tyco settlement===\nIn July 2007, PwC agreed to pay US$229 million to settle a class-action lawsuit brought by shareholders of [[Tyco International Ltd.]] over a multibillion-dollar accounting fraud. The chief executive and chief financial officer of Tyco were found guilty of looting $600 million from the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/tnBasicIndustries-SP/idUSN0619694620070706 |title=Pricewaterhouse to pay $225 mln in Tyco settlement |agency=Reuters | date=6 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Satyam case===\nIn January 2009 PwC was criticised,<ref name=\"Reuters08Jan2009-PwC\">{{cite news|last=Chen |first=George |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/companyNews/idINHKG30879120090108 |title=Satyam scandal rattles confidence in accounting Big Four |publisher=In.reuters.com |date=8 January 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"ET-PwC\">{{cite news|author=ET |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/3950021.cms |title=PwC's fate Hangs in Balance |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=8 January 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"ICAI-PwC-explanation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/2009/01/07165018/ICAI-to-seek-explanation-from.html |title=ICAI to seek explanation from Satyam's auditor PwC |publisher=Livemint.com |date=7 January 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"PwC-Satyam-explanation\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/marketsNews/idINBMA00213420090107?rpc=44 |title=Satyam auditor says examining chairman's statement |agency=Reuters | date=7 January 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Rediff-PwC-Satyam-\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2009/jan/07satyam-satyam-auditors-body-to-pull-up-pwc.htm |title=Satyam: Auditors' body to pull up PwC ICAI to seek explanation from Satyam's auditor PwC |publisher=Rediff.com }}</ref> along with the promoters of [[Satyam Computer Services|Satyam]], an Indian IT firm listed on the [[NASDAQ]], in a $1.5 billion fraud.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Satyam_A_Rs_7000_Cr_Lie/articleshow/3949109.cms |title=Satyam: A Rs 7,000cr Lie |work=The Times of India |date=8 January 2009 }}</ref> PwC wrote a letter to the board of directors of Satyam that its audit may be rendered \"inaccurate and unreliable\" due to the disclosures made by Satyam's (ex) Chairman and subsequently withdrew its audit opinions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssTechMediaTelecomNews/idUSBMA00217420090114 |title=PWC says Satyam audit opinions may be unreliable |agency=Reuters | date=14 January 2009}}</ref> PwC's US arm \"was the reviewer for the U.S. filings for Satyam.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/francinemckenna/2011/05/06/the-grand-illusion-pwc-settles-satyam-u-s-class-action-claims/2/#6542929e11dc|title=The Grand Illusion: PwC Settles Satyam U.S. Class Action Claims|last=McKenna|first=Francine|work=Forbes|access-date=9 May 2017}}</ref> Consequently, lawsuits have been filed in the US with PwC as a defendant. Two partners of PricewaterhouseCoopers, Srinivas Talluri and Subramani Gopalakrishnan, have been charged by India's [[Central Bureau of Investigation]] in connection with the [[Satyam Computer Services|Satyam]] scandal. Since the scandal broke out, Subramani Gopalakrishnan has retired from the firm after reaching mandatory retirement age, while Talluri remains on suspension from the firm.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.accountancyage.com/accountancyage/news/2240046/styam-partners-charged |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120722124303/http://www.accountancyage.com/accountancyage/news/2240046/styam-partners-charged |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 July 2012 |title=PwC partners charged over Satyam |date=8 April 2009 |author1=Raghavendra Verma |author2=Keith Nuthall |magazine=Accountancy Age |accessdate=1 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/29/business/global/29prison.html|title=Two Auditors Held in India Fault System|last=Timmons|first=Heather|date=28 May 2009|website=New York Times|access-date=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 PwC India said they were disappointed with court judgement of the case saying, \u201cAs we have said many times, there has never been any evidence presented that either of our former partners S Gopalakrishnan or Srinivas Talluri were involved in or were aware of the management-led fraud at Satyam. We understand that Gopal and Talluri are considering filing an appeal against this verdict.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/info-tech/disappointed-with-verdict-says-pwc/article7084946.ece|title=Disappointed with verdict, says PwC|last=Kumar|first=V Rishi|date=9 April 2015|work=The Hindu Business Line|access-date=9 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> In 2018, PwC was banned by India's securities regulator from providing auditing services to public-listed companies for 2 years, PwC was fined $2 million in addition to the suspension.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-bans-pricewaterhousecoopers-from-auditing-listed-firms-for-two-years-1515656186|title=India Bans PricewaterhouseCoopers From Auditing Listed Firms for Two Years|last=Abrams|first=Corinne|date=11 January 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=11 January 2018|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Subsequently, in September 2019, this ban was overruled by the securities appellate tribunal stating that there was no evidence of collusion of PwC in the scam. The tribunal also stated that SEBI had no jurisdiction over audit firms and only ICAI could issue such an order.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/consultancy-/-audit/sat-quashes-sebi-order-of-banning-pwc-for-two-years-from-auditing/articleshow/71044512.cms|title=SAT quashes Sebi order of banning PwC for two years from auditing|last=Dave|first=Sachin|date=2019-09-10|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-09-10|last2=Vyas|first2=Maulik}}</ref>\n\n===Yukos prosecutions===\n[[Yukos]] was a Russian oil and gas company that was the target of politically motivated prosecutions by Russian authorities. The company's assets were sold for alleged unpaid taxes and it was declared bankrupt. PwC's audits were the foundation for the firm's defense in a series of continuing trials against former chief executive, [[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]], and the former majority shareholder, [[Platon Lebedev]]. The Russian authorities then went after PwC. In March 2007 police raided PwC's Moscow offices, confiscating documents related to Yukos and charging and convicting PwC of failing to pay 243 million rubles, or $9.4 million, in taxes. PwC withdrew its Yukos audits and less than two weeks later authorities cleared PwC of any wrongdoing in regard to its audit.<ref name=\"Law 360: Russian Officials Clear PwC Of Fraud In Yukos Audit\">{{cite web|last1=Zapata|first1=Ron|title=Russian Officials Clear PwC Of Fraud In Yukos Audit|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/29939/russian-officials-clear-pwc-of-fraud-in-yukos-audit|publisher=Law 360|accessdate=11 May 2017|date=18 July 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes: Russian court hands victory to PricewaterhouseCoopers in tax evasion case\">{{cite news|last1=Elder|first1=Miriam|title=Russian court hands victory to PricewaterhouseCoopers in tax evasion case|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/10/business/worldbusiness/10iht-pwc.4.6595461.html|publisher=NYTimes|accessdate=11 May 2017|date=10 July 2007}}</ref>\n\n\"In 2007, with the prospect of parole on the horizon, the same prosecutors\u2014with what appears to be the complicity of PricewaterhouseCoopers, [[Yukos]]'s longtime accounting firm\u2014indicted the two men (Mikhail B. Khodorkovsky and Platon Lebedev), again, bringing a new round of Kafkaesque charges.\"<ref>''New York Times'' issue of 6 November 2010, business columnist [[Joe Nocera]]</ref>\n\nIn 2010, it was revealed that the Russian government placed pressure on PwC to withdraw audits.<ref name=\"The Globe and Mail: Rule of law crucial for safe investment\">{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Tony|title=Rule of law crucial for safe investment|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/small-business/sb-managing/rule-of-law-crucial-for-safe-investment/article626488/|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=11 May 2017|date=4 January 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal: Oil Tycoon Says PWC Caved to Pressure\">{{cite news|last1=White|first1=Gregory L|title=Oil Tycoon Says PWC Caved to Pressure|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704095704575473630120957538|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=11 May 2017|date=7 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nA cable from the U.S. embassy in Moscow stated that the trial was politically motivated and that a deposition in a U.S. court by PricewaterhouseCoopers may show that PwC was pressured by the Russian government to withdraw its prior Yukos audits. An embassy source noted that if the audits were not properly withdrawn it \"would greatly tarnish PWC's international reputation.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/khodorkovsky-case-discussed-in-leaked-cable/425531.html |work=The Moscow Times |title=Khodorkovsky Case Discussed in Leaked Cable |date=3 December 2010|accessdate=28 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/your-business/start/tony-wilson/rule-of-law-crucial-for-safe-investment/article1856706/ |work=The Globe and Mail |title=Rule of law crucial for safe investment |date=4 January 2010|accessdate=4 January 2010|location=Toronto |first=Tony|last=Wilson}}</ref>\n\n===Global Trust Bank Ltd and DSQ Software===\nIndia's accounting standards agency [[Institute of Chartered Accountants of India|ICAI]] is investigating partners of PwC for [[Professional negligence in English Law|professional negligence]]<ref name=\"ET-PwC\"/> in the now-defunct Global Trust Bank Ltd. case of 2007. Like Satyam, [[Global Trust Bank (India)|Global Trust Bank]] was also based in [[Hyderabad, Telangana|Hyderabad]]. This led to the [[Reserve Bank of India|RBI]] banning PwC from auditing any financial company for over a year.<ref name=\"BS-PwC\">{{cite web|author=Business Standard |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/storypage.php?autono=316917 |title=RBI lifts ban on PwC |publisher=Business-standard.com |date=15 March 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"BS-PwC-tax-evasion\">{{cite web|author=Business Standard |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/pwc-haschequered-pasttaxmen/09/24/345674/ |title=PwC has a chequered past with taxmen |publisher=Business-standard.com }}</ref><ref name=\"BS-PwC-blacklist\">{{cite web|author=Business Standard |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/regulator-may-blacklist-price-waterhouse/09/24/345651/ |title=Regulator may blacklist Price Waterhouse |publisher=Business-standard.com }}</ref> PwC was also associated with the accounting scandal at DSQ Software<ref name=\"DSQ-PwC\">{{cite web|last=Mukherjee |first=Ritwik |url=http://www.mydigitalfc.com/companies/third-mess-pwc-after-gtb-dsq-soft-210 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208092150/http://www.mydigitalfc.com/companies/third-mess-pwc-after-gtb-dsq-soft-210 |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 February 2009 |title=Third mess-up by PwC after GTB, DSQ Soft |publisher=Mydigitalfc.com |df= }}</ref> in India. Following the Satyam scandal, the Mumbai-based Small Investor Grievances Association (SIGA) has requested the Indian stock market regulator SEBI to ban PwC permanently and seize its assets in India alleging more scandals like \"Ketan Parekh stock manipulations.\"<ref name=\"SGAI-PwC\">{{cite web|author=Business Standard |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/investor-group-wants-sebi-to-supersede-satyam-board/19/56/52475/on |title=Investor group wants Sebi to supersede Satyam board |publisher=Business-standard.com }}</ref>\n\n===Transneft Russia case===\nUpon the completion of the construction of the ESPO (East Siberia-Pacific Ocean) pipeline by [[Transneft]]in December 2010, an official report of the Audit Chamber of the Russian Federation suggested that $4 billion was stolen by Transneft insiders.<ref name=\"Transneft\">{{cite news| url=http://www.times.spb.ru/index.php?story_id=32970&action_id=2| work=The St. Petersburg Times | title=Transneft Accused Of Stealing $4 Billion | date=19 November 2010 |accessdate=28 December 2010}}</ref> One Federation Council Speaker, Sergei Mironov, called for an investigation. [[Alexei Navalny]], a minority Transneft shareholder and lawyer, accused the company of wrongdoing in his personal blog, and criticized PwC, Transneft's auditor, of ignoring his warnings. PwC denied wrongdoing, stating that, \u201cWe believe there are absolutely no grounds for such allegations, and we stand behind our work for OAO AK Transneft.\u201d<ref name=\"The Moscow Times: Transneft Accused of $4Bln Theft\">{{cite news|last1=Amos|first1=Howard|title=Transneft Accused of $4Bln Theft|url=https://themoscowtimes.com/articles/transneft-accused-of-4bln-theft-3083|newspaper=The Moscow Times|accessdate=11 May 2017|date=18 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Northern Rock===\nIn 2007, PwC was criticised by the [[Treasury Select Committee]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] for helping [[Northern Rock]], a client of the firm, to sell its mortgage assets while also acting as its auditor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2011/mar/30/house-of-lords-uk-auditors-financial-crisis|title=MPs tackle PwC over Northern Rock|work=The Guardian|author=Alex Hawkes|date=30 March 2011|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/alistair-osborne/8417076/Were-Big-Four-auditors-just-guilty-of-failing-to-see-wood-for-trees.html |title=Were Big Four auditors just guilty of failing to see wood for trees?|work=The Daily Telegraph|author=Alistair Osborne|date=31 March 2011|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref> In 2011, a [[House of Lords]] inquiry criticized PwC for not drawing attention to the risks in the business model followed by Northern Rock, which was rescued by the UK government during the financial crisis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/dec/04/northernrock|title=House of Lords criticises UK auditors over role in financial crisis|work=The Guardian|author=Graeme Wearden|date=4 December 2011|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accountancyage.com/aa/news/1772315/pwc-urged-return-northern-rock-fees|title=PwC urged to return Northern Rock fees|work=Accountancy Age|author=David Jetuah|date=4 December 2011|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===JP Morgan Securities audit===\nIn 2012, the Accountancy and Actuarial Discipline Board (AADB) of the UK fined PwC a record \u00a31.4m for wrongly reporting to the Financial Services Authority that JP Morgan Securities had complied with client money rules which protects client funds. The accountants neglected to check whether JP Morgan had the correct systems in place, and failed to gather sufficient evidence to form opinions on the issue, and as a result, failed to report that JP Morgan failed to hold client money separate from JP Morgan's money. It is the greatest penalty administered to a professional accountancy firm in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/supportservices/8995981/PwC-fined-record-1.4m-over-JP-Morgan-audit.html |title=PwC fined record \u00a31.4m over JP Morgan audit |date=5 January 2012 |author=Anna White |work=The Daily Telegraph }}</ref>\n\n===Water privatisation in Delhi===\nPwC was found to be unethically favored by the [[World Bank]] in a bid to privatize the water distribution system of [[Delhi]], India, an effort that was alleged as corrupt by investigators.<ref name=\"MoneyLife\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moneylife.in/article/rti-expose-of-how-world-bank-had-arm-twisted-delhi-jal-board-for-water-privatisation/23217.html|title=RTI expose of how World Bank had arm-twisted Delhi Jal Board for water privatisation |work=Moneylife}}</ref> When bidding took place, PwC repeatedly failed in each round, and the World Bank in each case pressured PwC to be pushed to the next round and eventually win the bid. The effort at privatization fell through when an investigation was conducted by [[Arvind Kejriwal]] and the non-governmental organization (NGO) [[Arvind Kejriwal#Parivartan|Parivartan]] in 2005.<ref name=\"MoneyLife\" /> After submitting a [[Right to Information]] (RTI) request, Parivartan received 9000 pages of correspondence and consultation with the World Bank, where it was revealed that the privatization of Delhi's water supply would provide salaries of $25,000 a month to four administrators of each of the 21 water zones, which amounted to over $25 million per year, increasing the budget by over 60% and water taxes 9 times.<ref name=\"World Bank Tribunal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbanktribunal.org/Delhi_privatisation.html|title=Independent People's Tribunal on The World Bank in India: Program: Arvind Kejriwal|work=worldbanktribunal.org}}</ref><ref name=\"Youtube\">{{YouTube|-tqaLMOgPH0|''How World-Bank Dicatates Indian Policies''}}. BharatKiAwaaz.</ref>\n\nThe [[Delhi Jal Board]] (DJB), which administers the water system of Delhi, was first approached by Parivartan in November 2004, following a report by the newspaper ''[[The Asian Age]]'', where the scheme was revealed to the public for the first time.<ref name=\"World Bank Tribunal\" /><ref name=\"Youtube\" /> The DJB denied the existence of the project, but after an appeal, the RTI request was granted. The documents revealed that the project began in 1998, in complete secrecy within the DJB administration.<ref name=\"World Bank Tribunal\" /><ref name=\"Youtube\" /> The DJB approached the World Bank for a loan to improve the water system, which it approved, and the effort began with a $2.5 million consultation loan. The Delhi government could have easily provided the money, and the interest rate of 12% that was to be loaned by the World Bank could have been raised on capital markets for 6%.<ref name=\"World Bank Tribunal\" /><ref name=\"Youtube\" /> Following the consultation, 35 multi-national companies bid, of which six were to be short listed. When PwC was in 10th place, the World Bank said that at least one company should be from a developing country, and since PwC made the bid from its [[Kolkata]] office, it was dubbed an \"Indian\" company, and its rank was dropped to 6th.<ref name=\"MoneyLife\" /> When PwC failed in the second round, the World Bank pressured the DJB to start over with a fresh round of bidding. Only one company succeeded in the new round that was not PwC, and the World Bank had the lowest marks from an evaluator thrown out. The contract was awarded to PwC in 2001.<ref name=\"Commonwealth\">{{cite web |url=http://www.humanrightsinitiative.org/programs/ai/rti/india/states/delhi/rti_spurs_debate_on_world_bank_delhi_water_project.pdf |title=RTI Spurs Debate on World Bank Involvement in Delhi Water Deal |publisher=Commonwealth Human Rights Initiative}}</ref> Following the investigation by Parivartan, a campaign was waged by Kejriwal, [[Aruna Roy]], and other activists across Delhi, and the DJB withdrew the loan application to the World Bank.<ref name=\"MoneyLife\" /><ref name=\"World Bank Tribunal\" /><ref name=\"Youtube\" />\n\n===Cattles===\nIn 2013 [[Cattles]] plc brought a legal action against PwC in the UK in respect of the 2006 and 2007 audits claiming that they had failed to carry out adequate investigations.<ref>[http://economia.icaew.com/news/march-2013/pwc-failed-as-competent-auditor PwC failed as \"competent auditor\"] Economia March 2013</ref> Cattles, a UK consumer finance company, later discovered control weaknesses which caused its loan book to be materially overstated in its balance sheet; having been listed as a FTSE250 company, it subsequently lost its listing.  PwC disputed this legal claim.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/business/industries/supportservices/article3815554.ece Cattles\u2019 failure was nothing to do with us, says angry PwC] The Times, 17 July 2013</ref>  The claim was settled out of court on undisclosed terms.<ref>[http://economia.icaew.com/news/october-2015/pwc-settles-cattles-lawsuit PwC settles Cattles lawsuit] Economia October 2015</ref>\n\nThe [[Financial Reporting Council]] (FRC) issued a fine of \u00a32.3m on PwC and ordered the firm to pay \u00a3750,000 costs following their investigation of the 2007 audits of Cattles and its principal trading subsidiary.  PwC admitted their \u201cconduct fell significantly short of the standards reasonably to be expected of a member firm\u201d in respect of the 2007 financial statements. The FRC said that PwC had insufficient audit evidence as to the adequacy of loan loss provisions.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/aug/31/pwc-fined-over-auditing-of-subprime-lender-cattles PwC fined \u00a32.3m over auditing of subprime lender Cattles] The Guardian 31 August 2016</ref>\n\n===PCAOB report on audit inspections===\nThe [[Public Company Accounting Oversight Board]] (PCAOB) report on audit work carried out by PwC in 2014 in respect of US public companies identified significant deficiencies in 17 of 58 audits examined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pcaobus.org/Inspections/Reports/Documents/2015_PwC.pdf|title=Report on 2014 Inspection of PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP|last=|first=|date=30 June 2015|website=PCAOB: Public Company Accounting Oversight Board|access-date=10 May 2017}}</ref> The PCAOB report on work carried out in 2015 identified significant deficiencies in 12 of 55 audits examined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pcaobus.org/Inspections/Reports/Documents/104-2016-140-PwC.pdf|title=Report on 2015 Inspection of PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP|last=|first=|date=10 August 2016|website=Public Company Accounting Oversight Board: PCAOB|access-date=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Quinn Insurance===\nPwC Ireland is being sued by the joint administrators of Quinn Insurance Limited (QIL) for \u20ac1bn.  Having been audited by PwC for the years 2005 to 2008, QIL went into administration in 2010. The administrators allege that PwC should have identified a material understatement of QIL's provisions for claims.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/business/financial-services/pwc-claims-1bn-quinn-insurance-action-poised-on-cliff-1.2202607|title=PwC claims \u20ac1bn Quinn Insurance action 'poised on cliff'| newspaper=Irish Times|date=7 May 2015|accessdate=12 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/business/2015/0519/702340-quinn-insurance-pwc/ |title=More details sought in case against PWC over Quinn Insurance accounts| publisher= RTE News|date=19 May 2015|accessdate=12 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Connaught plc===\n[[Connaught plc]], a UK former [[FTSE 250 Index]] outsourcing company operating in property maintenance for the social housing and public sector, was put into administration on 2010 after reporting material losses.  In 2017, the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) severely reprimanded PwC and its audit partner following an investigation of their conduct in respect of the 2009 audit of Connaught.  PwC was fined a record \u00a35 million plus costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-39881001|title=PwC fined \u00a35m over Connaught audit|publisher=BBC|date=11 May 2017|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tesco===\nIn 2014 [[Tesco]], a UK retailer, announced that it had overstated profits by \u00a3263m by misreporting discounts with suppliers. The Financial Reporting Council started an investigation into accounting practices at Tesco and into the conduct of PwC in carrying out its audits in 2012, 2013 and 2014.<ref>[http://economia.icaew.com/news/december-2014/frc-launches-pwc-tesco-investigation FRC launches Tesco investigation] Economia December 2014</ref>  Two members of Tesco's Audit Committee, responsible for monitoring Tesco's relationship with its auditors, had themselves previously worked for PwC, including its chairman, Ken Hanna; he later stood down.<ref>[http://economia.icaew.com/opinion/october-2014/tesco-an-opportunity-for-audit Tesco : an opportunity for audit] Economia October 2014</ref> In 2015 PwC were replaced as auditors of Tesco, ending a 32-year engagement, following a tender process to which they did not participate.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-11/tesco-ends-32-year-pwc-relationship-after-accounting-scandal Tesco Ends 32-Year PwC Relationship After Accounting Scandal] Bloomberg.com May 2015</ref> In June 2017 the Financial Reporting Council said there was no \"realistic prospect\" that a tribunal of the UK's accountancy watchdog would rule against the auditor PwC concerning its involvement in [[Tesco]]'s 2014 case.<ref name=\"Financial Times: Accounting watchdog closes PwC/Tesco probe\">{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Kate|title=Accounting watchdog closes PwC/Tesco probe|url=https://www.ft.com/content/7a03dfa3-72cc-3af3-9950-ceb61b3f6f57|newspaper=Financial Times|accessdate=6 June 2017|date=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi UFJ===\nIn 2014, [[The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi UFJ]] was investigated by New York banking regulators over its role in routing payments for Iranian customers through its New York branch in violation of U.S. sanctions. It was found that PwC had altered an investigation report on the issue; PwC itself was fined $25 million in relation to the matter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bank of Tokyo Fined for 'Misleading' New York Regulator on Iran|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/11/18/lawsky-fines-bank-of-tokyo-mitsubishi-ufj-another-315-million/|accessdate=10 April 2015|work=New York Times DealBook|date=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Luxembourg Leaks===\n{{Main|Luxembourg Leaks}}\n[[File:Tax ruling luxembourg.png|thumb|One of the tax rulings of ''Luxembourg Leaks'' negotiated by PwC]]\nThe firm helped multinational companies obtain 548 legal tax rulings in Luxembourg between 2002 and 2010. The rulings provide written assurance that companies\u2019 tax-saving plans will be seen favorably by the Luxembourg authorities. The companies saved billions of dollars in taxes with these arrangements. Some firms paid less than one percent tax on the profits they shifted to Luxembourg. Employees or former employees of PwC provided documentation of the rulings to journalists.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.icij.org/project/luxembourg-leaks/your-head-spinning-5-tips-understand-lux-leaks-files|title=Is Your Head Spinning? 5 Tips to Understand the 'Lux Leaks' Files|work=International Consortium of Investigative Journalists|access-date=10 May 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>ICIJ [http://www.icij.org/project/luxembourg-leaks/explore-documents-luxembourg-leaks-database Explore the Documents: Luxembourg Leaks Database]</ref> PwC UK's head of tax was before the UK's public accounts committee and was questioned about lying regarding the marketing of these tax avoidance schemes. He told the committee the financing, investments and tax structure is legal and well known to the British government. \u201cIf you want to change the Lux tax regime, the politicians could change the Lux tax regime.\u201d<ref>The Guardian, [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/dec/08/pwc-kevin-nicholson-tax-scheme-mps-luxembourg PriceWaterhouseCoopers chief Kevin Nicholson denies lying over tax deals]</ref> The disclosures attracted international attention and comment about tax avoidance schemes in Luxembourg and other tax havens. The revelations later led to a series of EU-wide measures aimed at regulating tax avoidance schemes and tax probes into several EU companies. PwC initiated charges against the two whistleblowers that revealed the LuxLeaks tax controversy. In March 2017 a Luxembourg appeals court upheld their convictions, but with reduced sentences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/luxleaks-whistleblowers-get-lighter-sentences/|title=LuxLeaks whistleblowers get lighter sentences|last=Ari\u00e8s|first=Quentin|date=15 March 2017|website=Politico|access-date=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Petrobras Brazil===\nThe [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]] by [[Microsoft]] founder [[Bill Gates]] has sued [[Petrobras]] and accounting firm PwC Brazil arm over investment losses due to corruption at the Brazilian oil company.  The filings have also alleged that PwC's Brazil affiliate, PricewaterhouseCoopers Auditores Independentes, played a significant role by attesting to Petrobras financial statements and ignoring warnings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/oilandgas/11892400/Bill-Gates-sues-oil-giant-Petrobras-and-PwC-over-corruption-scandal.html|title=Bill Gates sues oil giant Petrobras and PwC over corruption scandal|website=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Australia ===\nCEO, Luke Sayers,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/brand/boss/pwc-boss-luke-sayers-thrives-in-adversity-20160517-gowtd5|title=Luke Sayers, corporate politician|date=8 September 2016|work=Financial Review|access-date=13 August 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big4.com/pricewaterhousecoopers/pwc-australia-appoints-new-ceo/|title=PwC Australia Appoints New CEO {{!}} Big4.com|website=www.big4.com|language=en-US|access-date=13 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813143516/http://www.big4.com/pricewaterhousecoopers/pwc-australia-appoints-new-ceo/|archive-date=13 August 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is a vocal supporter of [[gay marriage]] and had the firm prepare a report in 2016 projecting the excessive cost of a plebiscite on the issue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-03-14/525-million-price-tag-on-same-sex-marriage-plebiscite-study/7243298|title=Same-sex marriage vote has $525m price tag, study finds|date=14 March 2016|work=ABC News|access-date=13 August 2017|language=en-AU}}</ref> Mark Allaby, a senior executive at PwC, left the board of the [[Australian Christian Lobby]], a group campaigning against same-sex marriage, following outrage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2016/03/01/pwc-exec-leaves-australian-christian-lobby-board/|title=PwC exec leaves Australian Christian Lobby board|date=1 March 2016|website=Crikey|access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nShopping center giant [[Centro Properties Group|Centro]] understated its current liabilities by more than $3\u2009billion and almost collapsed when it was unable to refinance its debt during the global financial crisis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/real-estate/commercial/centro-pwc-take-record-200m-legal-hit-20120508-j2v7s|title=Centro, PwC take record $200m legal hit|date=9 May 2012|work=Financial Review|access-date=13 August 2017|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813143154/http://www.afr.com/real-estate/commercial/centro-pwc-take-record-200m-legal-hit-20120508-j2v7s|archive-date=13 August 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> PwC was Centro's auditor and admitted negligence. Centro and PwC paid a $200 million settlement to resolve the shareholder class action, the largest ever in Australia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/pwc-auditor-sidelined-until-2015-for-21b-centro-debt-bungle-20121119-29m5v.html|title=PwC auditor sidelined until 2015 for $2.1b Centro debt bungle|last=Battersby|first=Lucy|date=20 November 2012|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=13 August 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===BHS===\nPwC in the UK is being investigated by the Financial Reporting Council over its conduct in relation to the audit of [[British Home Stores|BHS]] for the year to 30 August 2014.  PwC completed their audit of financial statements in which BHS was described as a going concern days before its sale for \u00a31 to a consortium with no retail experience.  BHS collapsed the following year with a substantial deficit in its pension fund.<ref>[https://www.accountancyage.com/2016/05/24/pwc-questioned-over-bhs-going-concern-audit/ PwC questioned over BHS \u2018going concern\u2019 audit] Accountancy Age May 2016</ref>\n\n===MF Global malpractice lawsuit===\nIn 2016, [[United States federal judge]] rejected PwC's bid to dismiss a $3 billion lawsuit accusing the accounting firm of professional malpractice for helping cause the October 2011 bankruptcy of MF Global Holdings Ltd, a brokerage once run by former New Jersey Governor [[Jon Corzine]].<ref name=\"pwC MF lawsuit\">{{cite web|title=PwC must face $1 billion MF Global malpractice lawsuit: U.S. judge|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mfglobal-pwc-decision-idUSKCN10G1VJ?il=0|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Global Lawsuit\">{{cite web|title=Judge Says MF Global Lawsuit Against PwC Can Proceed|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-says-mf-global-lawsuit-against-pwc-can-proceed-1470427038|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Audit Lawsuit\">{{cite web|title=Largest lawsuit against an auditor goes to court for $5.5 billion|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/business/banking/article92700782.html|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===BT Italy===\n[[BT Group]] (British Telecom), a client of PwC, reported in 2017 that profits in its Italian subsidiary had been over-stated by \u00a3530 million.  BT reportedly sought the immediate replacement of PwC as auditors following a breakdown of trust, but had existing commercial relationships with the other Big 4 firms which would have prevented their early appointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/bt-in-urgent-hunt-for-clean-auditor-after-163530m-italy-scandal-10817472|title=BT in urgent hunt for 'clean' auditor after \u00a3530m Italy scandal |publisher=Sky News |date=29 March 2017|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>  BT subsequently stated that its audit would be put out to tender to identify a replacement for PwC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economia.icaew.com/en/news/may-2017/bt-looking-for-new-auditor-after-33-years-with-pwc|title=BT looking for new auditor after 33 years with PwC|publisher=Economia|date=12 May 2017|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref> The Financial Reporting Council has begun an investigation of PwC's audit of BT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-40441128|title=BT Italy scandal prompts auditing probe|publisher=BBC|date=29 June 2017|accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Lezo Case ===\nPwC Spain is being investigated by the [[Audiencia Nacional (Spain)|Spanish National Court]] as part of the [[People's Party (Spain)#Lezo Case|Lezo Case]] for participating in and profiting from the embezzlement of public funds to illegally finance the [[People's Party (Spain)|People's Party]] (PP) political party in the [[Community of Madrid]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/espana/2017/04/30/5906349ee2704ee81a8b4680.html|title=El juez acredita que PwC se lucr\u00f3 de un contrato fantasma a cambio de financiar al PP de Madrid|work=ELMUNDO|access-date=2 June 2017|language=es}}</ref>\n\n=== PrivatBank ===\nPwC Ukraine had its audit license removed by the [[National Bank of Ukraine]] in July 2017 for its alleged \"verification of misrepresented financial information\" leading to a $5.5 billion balance-sheet hole in [[PrivatBank]].<ref name=ft-20170720>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/9a46c818-6d7e-11e7-b9c7-15af748b60d0 |title=Ukraine pulls PwC bank audit licence over $5.5bn hole at top lender |last=Olearchyk |first=Roman |newspaper=Financial Times |date=20 July 2017 |accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref>  The government of Ukraine had had to rescue PrivatBank by nationalisation in 2016 to protect its 20 million customers.<ref name=bbc-20161219>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-38365579 |title=Ukraine's biggest lender PrivatBank nationalised |work=BBC News |date=19 December 2016 |accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== ESNC case ===\nIn December 2016, researchers at ESNC discovered a vulnerability in PwC's software which could allow a malicious party to manipulate accounting documents and financial results, bypass change management controls, and bypass segregation of duties restrictions which could result in fraud, theft or manipulation of sensitive data, as well as the unauthorized payment transactions and transfer of money.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.esnc.de/security-advisories/vulnerability-in-pwc-ace-for-sap-security/index.html |title=[ESNC-2041217] Critical Security Vulnerability in PwC ACE Software for SAP Security |date=2016 |accessdate=2018-11-14}}</ref> PwC tried to suppress this research through legal means and a \"cease and desist\" order, but the researchers published their findings regardless.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://it.slashdot.org/story/16/12/13/053243/pwc-sends-legal-threats-to-researchers-who-found-critical-security-flaw |title=PwC Sends Legal Threats To Researchers Who Found Critical Security Flaw |date=2016 |accessdate= 2018-11-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Colonial Bank Audit ===\nIn 2017, the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of Alabama|U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Alabama]] held PwC liable for professional negligence in its audit of [[Colonial Bank (United States)|Colonial Bank]], which failed in 2009 after filing materially false financial information with the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]]. A federal judge later ordered PwC to pay the [[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation|FDIC]] $625 million in December, the largest-ever judgement against a U.S. audit firm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/colonial-bank-award-against-pwc-is-window-into-typically-secret-settlements-1530725672|title=Colonial Bank Award Against PWC Is Window Into Typically Secret Settlements|last=MarketWatch|first=Francine McKenna|date=2018-07-04|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-03-30|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> The FDIC reached a $335 million settlement with PwC in March 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/pricewaterhousecoopers-settles-with-fdic-over-failed-bank-audits-11552673898|title=PricewaterhouseCoopers Settles With FDIC Over Failed Bank Audits|last=Barba|first=Robert|date=2019-03-15|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-03-30|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n=== Age Discrimination Lawsuit ===\nIn 2016, PwC was accused of disproportionately hiring younger workers and fostering \"an age-conscious workplace in which youth is highly valued.\" <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/suit-claims-pwcs-campus-recruiting-disadvantages-older-job-seekers-1519850508|title=Campus Recruiting Hurts Older Workers, Suit Against PricewaterhouseCoopers Claims|last=Gee|first=Kelsey|date=2018-02-28|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-04-01|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Plaintiffs estimated that younger applicants are over 500% more likely to be hired than candidates over age 40. In March 2019, a collective action related to the case was certified by a federal judge in San Francisco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.com/therecorder/2019/03/28/pricewaterhousecoopers-faces-collective-action-in-age-bias-case/|title=PricewaterhouseCoopers Faces Collective Action in Age Bias Case|last=March 28|first=Ross Todd {{!}}|last2=PM|first2=2019 at 06:29|website=The Recorder|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Luke Sayers\u2019 AVP Investment Review ===\nIn 2018, PwC Australia CEO Luke Sayers was connected to perceived conflict of interest issues on a related to a personal investment in Australian Visa Processing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/street-talk/pwc-australia-to-review-partner-investments-after-global-intervention-20180716-h12q91|title=PwC Australia to review partner investments after global intervention|date=2018-07-16|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>   Australian Visa Processing (AVP) is a company part-owned by PwC that was submitting a tender to redesign and run Australia's visa processing system that is potentially worth billions of dollars, which would result in a significant financial advantage for its investors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itnews.com.au/news/home-affairs-1bn-visa-platform-outsourcing-riddled-with-it-risks-531488|title=Home Affairs $1bn visa platform outsourcing riddled with IT risks|website=iTnews|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> This investment led to a \u201cstorm inside the firm\u201d,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/street-talk/tension-lingers-at-pwc-over-visa-investments-20180919-h15kqu|title=Tension lingers at PwC over visa investments|date=2018-09-19|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> interjection by PwC Global and a review by PwC Australia of its personal investment policy for partners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/street-talk/tension-lingers-at-pwc-over-visa-investments-20180919-h15kqu|title=Tension lingers at PwC over visa investments|date=2018-09-19|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The option to invest had not been offered to all partners or even the entire firm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/street-talk/pwc-australia-to-review-partner-investments-after-global-intervention-20180716-h12q91|title=PwC Australia to review partner investments after global intervention|date=2018-07-16|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> A review was announced around the way partners make personal investments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/street-talk/pwc-australia-to-review-partner-investments-after-global-intervention-20180716-h12q91|title=PwC Australia to review partner investments after global intervention|date=2018-07-16|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/companies/professional-services/accountants-can-invest-in-consulting-clients-raising-conflict-fears-20180717-h12soh|title=Accountants can invest in consulting clients, raising conflict fears|date=2018-07-17|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Angola corruption ===\nIn 2020, the [[International Consortium of Investigative Journalists]] (ICIJ) leaked over 700,000 internal documents revealing that PwC had facilitated multiple dealings in which [[Isabel dos Santos]], the daughter of the former president of [[Angola]], made a fortune while in charge of the state oil company, [[Sonangol Group|Sonangol]]. Dos Santos established a network of over 400 companies to facilitate tax evasion and the steering of millions of dollars of Angolan state contracts to companies under her control.<ref name = \"Luanda Leaks\">{{cite web |last1=Freedberg |first1=Sydney P. |last2=Alecci |first2=Scilla |last3=Fitzgibbon |first3=Will |last4=Dalby |first4=Douglas |last5=Reuter |first5=Delphine |title=The Luanda Leaks: How Africa's Richest Woman Exploited Family Ties, Shell Companies And Inside Deals to Build an Empire |url=https://www.icij.org/investigations/luanda-leaks/how-africas-richest-woman-exploited-family-ties-shell-companies-and-inside-deals-to-build-an-empire/ |publisher=International Consortium of Investigative Journalism |accessdate=3 February 2020 |date=January 19, 2020}}</ref> Her husband, Congolese businessman and art collector [[Sindika Dokolo]], made millions from a suspiciously one-sided partnership with the state diamond company, Sodiam, to buy a stake in Swiss luxury jeweler [[De Grisogono]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51128950 |title=Isabel dos Santos: Africa's richest woman 'ripped off Angola' |last=BBC Panorama Team |date=20 January 2020 |website=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> After ICIJ's revelations, PwC indicated it would terminate its relationship with Dos Santos.<ref name = \"Luanda Leaks\"/>\n\n==Recognition==\n* Brand Finance ranked PwC among the world's 500 most valuable brands in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brandfinance.com/images/upload/global_500_2017_locked_website.pdf|title=Global 500 2017-The annual report on the world's most valuable brands.|last=|first=|date=February 2017|website=|access-date=15 May 2017}}</ref>\n* The company was recognized by The European Diversity Awards as the \u2018Most Inclusive Employer of the Year\u2019 in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europeandiversityawards.com/shortlist-2015/winners-2015/|title=European Diversity Awards \u00bb THE EDA WINNERS 2015|website=europeandiversityawards.com|language=en-US|access-date=15 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521211812/http://europeandiversityawards.com/shortlist-2015/winners-2015/|archive-date=21 May 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* PwC's Public Sector practice was awarded the [[Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Award]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nist.gov/baldrige/baldrige-award-111214.cfm|title=Four U.S. Organizations Honored With 2014 Baldrige National Quality Award|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref>\n* PwC received the full five stars on the BITC Corporate Responsibility Index for several years, and achieved it again in 2016 with a score of 99%. They were one of only four professional services companies to do so.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bitc.org.uk/services/benchmarking/cr-index/cr-index-2016-company-listing|title=CR Index 2016: Company listing|date=11 April 2016|work=Business in the Community|access-date=16 May 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211205456/http://www.bitc.org.uk/services/benchmarking/cr-index/cr-index-2016-company-listing|archive-date=11 February 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Gartner recognized PwC with a Top Rating for Financial Consulting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big4.com/news/gartner-gives-top-rating-to-pricewaterhousecoopers-for-financial-consulting/|title=Gartner Gives Top Rating to PricewaterhouseCoopers for Financial Consulting {{!}} Big4.com|website=www.big4.com|language=en-US|access-date=16 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707173003/http://www.big4.com/news/gartner-gives-top-rating-to-pricewaterhousecoopers-for-financial-consulting/|archive-date=7 July 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Accounting networks and associations]]\n* [[Big Four accounting firms]]: [[KPMG]], [[Ernst & Young|EY]], [[Deloitte]]\n* [[Crowe Global]], [[BDO Global]], [[Grant Thornton]]\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n* [[List of companies based in London]]\n* ''[[Price Waterhouse v Kwan]]''\n* [[Tax advisor]]\n* [[FTSE 100 Index]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''True and Fair: A History of Price Waterhouse'', Jones, E., 1995, Hamish Hamilton, {{ISBN|0-241-00172-2}}\n* ''An Early History of Coopers & Lybrand'', 1984, Garland Publishing Inc., {{ISBN|978-0-8240-6319-1}}\n* ''Accounting for Success: A History of Price Waterhouse in America 1890\u20131990 (1992)'' {{ISBN|0-875-843-28X}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|PricewaterhouseCoopers}}\n* {{Official web